A contented temper, we are apt to &s;ay, is a
great happine&s;s to tho&s;e who have it; and
a di&s;contented one, we call an unlucky turn
of mind; as if we were &s;peaking of a
good or bad con&s;titution of body, of &s;ome|thing
that depended not at all on our&s;elves,
but was merely the gift of Nature.&mdash;
Ought this to be the &s;entiment, either of a
