is di&s;po&s;ed for living well with others, and
&s;preads around him that cheerfulne&s;s which
he po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es; the re&s;tle&s;s di&s;contented per&s;on
is always a troubler of the world; neither
a good friend, nor a good neighbour, nor
a good &s;ubject or citizen.</P>
<P><PB N="160" REF="171">
IN the &s;econd place, as this di&s;po&s;ition
